{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "A better understanding of the workings of the brain means that psychiatric disorders are increasingly seen as being based in biology.", "abstract": "Gray Matter column by Nobel laureate Prof Eric R Kandel highlights advances made in the study of the brain that show that mental disorders are biological in nature; contends result of such work is a new, unified science of the mind that uses the combined power of cognitive psychology and neuroscience to examine how humans think, feel and experience themselves as conscious beings.", "section_name": "Opinion", "print_page": "12", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"lastname": "KANDEL", "rank": 1, "firstname": "Eric", "role": "reported", "organization": "", "middlename": "R."}], "original": "By ERIC R. KANDEL", "contributor": ""}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/08/opinion/sunday/the-new-science-of-mind.html", "lead_paragraph": "A better understanding of the workings of the brain means that psychiatric disorders are increasingly seen as being based in biology.", "headline": {"print_headline": "The New Science Of Mind", "main": "The New Science of Mind", "content_kicker": "Gray Matter", "kicker": "Gray Matter"}, "_id": "522a35ab38f0d8740ac9e310", "word_count": "1041", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2013/09/08/sunday-review/08GRAYMATTERsub/08GRAYMATTERsub-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2013/09/08/sunday-review/08GRAYMATTERsub/08GRAYMATTERsub-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 900, "url": "images/2013/09/08/sunday-review/08GRAYMATTERsub/08GRAYMATTERsub-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2013/09/08/sunday-review/08GRAYMATTERsub/08GRAYMATTERsub-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "900"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2013/09/08/sunday-review/08GRAYMATTERsub/08GRAYMAT